    "content": "nullGeneral Administration and Developer Help for Salesforce Industries...\nTABLE OF CONTENTS\nClose\nClose\nSearch\nSearch\n General Administration and Developer Help for Salesforce Industries...\n Bulk Async Engine For Cart APIs\n Async Engine Recommendations\n Async Engine Architecture\n Advanced Use of the Async Engine\n Async Engine APIs\n Develop with the Async Engine\n Async Process Tracking and Debugging\n Security of the Async Engine\n Limitations with the Async Engine\n Best Practices for the Async Engine\n Developer Documentation\n System Administration and Set Up\n Industries Data Models for Communications, Media, Energy,...\n\nYou are here:\n\nSALESFORCE HELP\nDOCS\nADMINISTRATION AND DEVELOPER HELP\nBulk Async Engine For Cart APIs\n\nSalesforce Asynchronous Apex offers multiple ways for running your Apex code asynchronously. However, creating complex processes that run efficiently on Apex can be time-consuming and difficult. The Async Engine abstracts the complexities of Apex to easily process long transactions and complex solutions. Developers can use the engine to create complex processes that are asynchronous and multi-threaded. Using the engine allows developers to increase throughput and reduce execution time. The Async Engine and its abstraction allows you to focus on business process and implementation.\n\nThe Apex runtime engine strictly enforces limits so that Apex code or processes don’t monopolize shared resources. However, these governor limits can also restrict complex processes from executing efficiently. The Async Engine allows developers to process larger volumes of data as fast as possible and create complex multi-step processes. Using the Async Engine allows you to simplify development and processing by:\n\nAbstracting the complexities of Asynchronous Apex features such as Future Apex, Batch Apex and, Queueable Apex.\n\nProviding a flexible framework that is easy to use and configure.\n\nFocusing on business capabilities instead of overcoming asynchronous technical challenges.\n\nReducing processing time with parallel executing using multi-threading.\n\nUtilize an optimized engine that performs async jobs as fast as possible. This avoids multiple teams coding their developed Async Apex solutions that each need to be optimized.\n\nScaling for large volumes of data by automatically splitting processes into several asynchronous Apex jobs that each allow higher governor limits.\n\nThe Async Engine uses Queueable Apex jobs to call or execute custom processes that can be VIP or Apex. The engine uses platform events to orchestrate the execution of processes. The data that is processed, that is defined in the Items to Process List, is then broken down into several independent jobs based on a configurable parameter. These jobs are executed in parallel.\n\nFor example, say you want to create 100 orders in 100 accounts and you created a solution called Create Order to handle this. However, it can only handle one account or order per transaction due to governor limits. You can instead pass the 100 accounts, order details, and your custom solution to the Apex Engine, The Async Engine processes the solution by creating 100 transactions that are Queueable Apex jobs. Each one of the 100 jobs then calls the Create Order solution with one account and order details. Each of these transactions is then executed in parallel up to a limit of 50. However, from a processing point of view, they're all executed in parallel and independently. In addition to this, since the Create Order solution is being executed asynchronously, it also has higher governor limits. Due to the higher limits, you can then choose to update your solution to instead accept a higher number of accounts. This allows each job to process a higher number of accounts allowing it to be more efficient and perform better.\n\nzYou can also use the Async Engine to chain the execution of one custom process to another. This allows an API call to perform a series of steps asynchronously and in parallel. Therefore for the example solution Create Order, you can now add extra steps to enhance the flow. Say that you want to update account details before creating the order. In addition to this, after the order is created, you want create extra order line items. You can separate your solution into three steps. The first step called \"Update Account Details\" updates the account information. Once the first step is complete, it calls the next step which creates the order. Once the Create Order step is done, it calls the final step called Create Order Line Items.\n\nAsync Engine Recommendations\nWe recommend using the Async Engine for several use cases, such as processing a large amount of data or using complex processes.\nAsync Engine Architecture\nThe Async Engine calls custom processes called async processes, which contain all the details to execute an API request. The Async Engine has important parameters, such as itemsToProcessList and additionalData.\nAdvanced Use of the Async Engine\nThe Async Engine is a general-purpose engine that can execute any code or process that is provided. It also allows customization in several places to allow you to create a Turin Complete solution.\nAsync Engine APIs\nYou can use either REST APIs or Apex with the Async Engine APIs.\nDevelop with the Async Engine\nUse the Async Engine to develop your own custom processes.\nAsync Process Tracking and Debugging\nTo track and debug processes, add the Async_Engine_Develop_and_Manage_Design permission set to your user. With this permission set, you can use the Async Process tab. Before adding permission sets to users, ensure that you're aware of the security implications.\nSecurity of the Async Engine\nThis section provides an overview of the security design of the Async Engine and how to create solutions that are secure by design.\nLimitations with the Async Engine\nThe Asynch Engine has some restrictions, such as API payload, processing, and maximum thread limits.\nBest Practices for the Async Engine\nReturn user-friendly message to display to an end-user and technical message to debug - Make sure your custom process return messages that can be shown to end-users (normally business error messages) and technical messages with the stack trace to help with debugging. If you don’t catch the error the Async Engine will and will log it.\nDID THIS ARTICLE SOLVE YOUR ISSUE?\nLet us know so we can improve!\nYes\nNo\n ",
